1
00:00:00,900 --> 00:00:05,730
Many traders are either unaware of the importance
of divergences or are unable to accurately

2
00:00:05,730 --> 00:00:07,760
apply the divergence concept.

3
00:00:07,760 --> 00:00:12,809
A divergence occurs when price and the indicators
provide conflicting signals by moving in opposite

4
00:00:12,809 --> 00:00:13,839
directions.

5
00:00:13,839 --> 00:00:17,970
If you spot such a situation, it could be
worthwhile taking a closer look at what is

6
00:00:17,970 --> 00:00:18,970
really going on.

7
00:00:18,970 --> 00:00:23,679
In today’s video we’ll talk about divergence
trading, and I will share 10 important rules

8
00:00:23,679 --> 00:00:28,039
you must follow to profit consistently from
market divergences.

9
00:00:28,039 --> 00:00:29,390
1.

10
00:00:29,390 --> 00:00:32,450
Use the right indicators to spot divergences

11
00:00:32,450 --> 00:00:37,950
Most of the technical indicators used to observe
divergences are momentum oscillators.

12
00:00:37,950 --> 00:00:43,410
But some indicators are better to find regular
divergences, while other are suited for hidden

13
00:00:43,410 --> 00:00:44,410
divergences.

14
00:00:44,410 --> 00:00:49,190
From my experience, oscillators that are used
to determine whether a market is overbought

15
00:00:49,190 --> 00:00:53,190
or oversold are more effective for spotting
hidden divergences.

16
00:00:53,190 --> 00:00:58,800
Stochastic indicator and RSI are perfect to
find hidden divergences, which happens when

17
00:00:58,800 --> 00:01:03,000
the technical indicator shows a new extreme,
but the corresponding price action does not.

18
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:08,990
For example, in this bullish hidden divergence,
the Stochastic makes a lower low while the

19
00:01:08,990 --> 00:01:10,710
price make a higher low.

20
00:01:10,710 --> 00:01:15,530
In essence, while the price is higher than
it was before, the indicator is lower, suggesting

21
00:01:15,530 --> 00:01:18,460
the market is much more oversold.

22
00:01:18,460 --> 00:01:23,240
In a hidden bearish divergence scenario, the
Stochastic makes a higher high while the price

23
00:01:23,240 --> 00:01:24,740
makes a lower high.

24
00:01:24,740 --> 00:01:29,440
Hidden divergences are also called continuation
divergences because are used to trade the

25
00:01:29,440 --> 00:01:32,270
continuation of a trend.

26
00:01:32,270 --> 00:01:37,290
For regular bullish and bearish indicators,
I found that MACD histogram and Money flow

27
00:01:37,290 --> 00:01:40,229
index are very effective to find such patterns.

28
00:01:40,229 --> 00:01:44,610
Bullish divergences are used to trade the
change in direction from a downwards move

29
00:01:44,610 --> 00:01:46,060
to an upwards move.

30
00:01:46,060 --> 00:01:50,870
They occur when price creates a lower low
and at the same time, the technical indicator,

31
00:01:50,870 --> 00:01:53,460
MACD in this example, is making a higher low.

32
00:01:53,460 --> 00:01:58,380
In essence, MACD is not following the price
down, suggesting the move lower is weakening

33
00:01:58,380 --> 00:02:03,550
and losing momentum, resulting in a possible
move higher.

34
00:02:03,550 --> 00:02:07,450
Bearish divergences are used to trade the
change in direction from an upwards move to

35
00:02:07,450 --> 00:02:09,099
a downwards move.

36
00:02:09,099 --> 00:02:13,489
They occur when price creates a higher high
and at the same time, the indicator is making

37
00:02:13,489 --> 00:02:14,840
a lower high.

38
00:02:14,840 --> 00:02:19,389
In this case, MACD is not following the price
up, suggesting the move higher is weakening

39
00:02:19,389 --> 00:02:23,590
and losing momentum, resulting in a possible
move lower.

40
00:02:23,590 --> 00:02:25,090
2.

41
00:02:25,090 --> 00:02:30,109
Adjust the settings of indicators to identify
divergences more easily

42
00:02:30,109 --> 00:02:34,629
For any given divergence indicator, there
will usually be different settings for different

43
00:02:34,629 --> 00:02:37,590
markets and different settings for different
time frames.

44
00:02:37,590 --> 00:02:41,629
Let’s say you prefer trading hidden divergences
with RSI.

45
00:02:41,629 --> 00:02:47,560
Here, the first 2 RSI settings were able to
spot the hidden divergence, while the smoother

46
00:02:47,560 --> 00:02:51,469
RSI, with the longer period, was unable to
find it.

47
00:02:51,469 --> 00:02:58,510
So remember this: higher lookback periods
on indicators will not suit hidden divergences.

48
00:02:58,510 --> 00:03:00,480
The same for regular divergences.

49
00:03:00,480 --> 00:03:02,919
Larger settings will produce a higher lag.

50
00:03:02,919 --> 00:03:07,719
Of course, there will be periods when market
volatility and momentum cycles will change

51
00:03:07,719 --> 00:03:11,730
and the indicator settings you have been using
will be much less useful.

52
00:03:11,730 --> 00:03:18,480
So you may need to slightly shorten or increase
the lookback period to find the optimal divergences.

53
00:03:18,480 --> 00:03:20,010
3.

54
00:03:20,010 --> 00:03:23,439
Only take divergences in the direction of
the main trend

55
00:03:23,439 --> 00:03:28,590
With regular divergences, the oscillators
indicate momentum shift and thus, point toward

56
00:03:28,590 --> 00:03:30,560
a reversal of the trend.

57
00:03:30,560 --> 00:03:35,139
This implies that a regular divergence warns
the end of a trend is expected.

58
00:03:35,139 --> 00:03:39,430
Hidden divergences signal momentum coming
into the main trend, suggesting a possible

59
00:03:39,430 --> 00:03:42,180
continuation in the main direction of the
trend.

60
00:03:42,180 --> 00:03:46,799
Now, the reason why so many traders fail when
taking divergence signals is because they

61
00:03:46,799 --> 00:03:48,889
take counter-trend signals.

62
00:03:48,889 --> 00:03:53,760
They spot a regular divergence and immediately
think the market will reverse.

63
00:03:53,760 --> 00:03:59,519
A smarter way to trade divergences, is to
identify the main trend and find divergences

64
00:03:59,519 --> 00:04:01,930
that go along with the trend.

65
00:04:01,930 --> 00:04:06,969
In the case of an uptrend, you ignore bearish
regular divergences (those appearing on the

66
00:04:06,969 --> 00:04:10,819
top of the oscillator) and search for bullish
regular divergences.

67
00:04:10,819 --> 00:04:16,169
In addition, you also concentrate on bullish
hidden divergences.

68
00:04:16,169 --> 00:04:21,110
In the case of a downtrend, you ignore bullish
regular divergences and search for bearish

69
00:04:21,110 --> 00:04:24,810
regular divergences and bearish hidden divergences.

70
00:04:24,810 --> 00:04:29,930
In this way, you have a higher probability
of a successful divergence trade.

71
00:04:29,930 --> 00:04:31,710
4.

72
00:04:31,710 --> 00:04:36,080
Always wait for price action confirmation
(trend line breakout)

73
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:40,340
While using divergences is a great tool to
have in your trading toolbox, there are times

74
00:04:40,340 --> 00:04:44,180
when you might enter too early because you
did not wait for more confirmation.

75
00:04:44,180 --> 00:04:47,460
And a divergence signal always needs a confirmation.

76
00:04:47,460 --> 00:04:52,050
If you keep entering divergences too early,
you’ll keep getting stopped out and you’ll

77
00:04:52,050 --> 00:04:53,520
slowly rack up losses.

78
00:04:53,520 --> 00:04:57,020
The best confirmation is a trend line break
out.

79
00:04:57,020 --> 00:05:02,060
When a divergence forms and the price starts
changing direction and breaks a trend line,

80
00:05:02,060 --> 00:05:06,720
there is a higher probability the price is
going to reverse.

81
00:05:06,720 --> 00:05:13,290
This example shows a bullish MACD divergence
with a confirmed trend line breakout.

82
00:05:13,290 --> 00:05:17,990
So for better results, just wait for a trend
line breakout, or a support or resistance

83
00:05:17,990 --> 00:05:19,210
breakout.

84
00:05:19,210 --> 00:05:23,560
When you see price action breaking a major
level, it could signal a shift in power from

85
00:05:23,560 --> 00:05:28,669
buyers to sellers (or vice versa) and that
a price reversal might occurring.

86
00:05:28,669 --> 00:05:29,930
5.

87
00:05:29,930 --> 00:05:34,360
Take divergence signals from support/resistance
levels

88
00:05:34,360 --> 00:05:39,349
To avoid trade entries that don’t go anywhere,
I highly suggest you add other criteria and

89
00:05:39,349 --> 00:05:41,680
confirmation tools to your arsenal.

90
00:05:41,680 --> 00:05:46,440
Besides the trend line breakout, the location
of the divergence is very important.

91
00:05:46,440 --> 00:05:50,590
Adding the filter of location can usually
enhance the quality of your divergence signals

92
00:05:50,590 --> 00:05:51,970
and trades.

93
00:05:51,970 --> 00:05:56,750
Instead of taking trades just based on a divergence
signal, you’d wait for the price to move

94
00:05:56,750 --> 00:06:02,469
into a previous support/resistance zone and
only then look for divergences and trend shifts,

95
00:06:02,469 --> 00:06:04,340
to time your entries.

96
00:06:04,340 --> 00:06:09,480
In this example, you see an uptrend with two
divergences.

97
00:06:09,480 --> 00:06:15,110
However, the first one completely failed and
the second one resulted in a massive winner.

98
00:06:15,110 --> 00:06:16,800
What was the difference?

99
00:06:16,800 --> 00:06:21,060
When we analyze the big picture, we see that
the first divergences happened in the middle

100
00:06:21,060 --> 00:06:26,009
of nowhere and the second divergence formed
at a very important resistance level.

101
00:06:26,009 --> 00:06:32,490
As a trader, you first identify your support/resistance
zones and then let price come to you.

102
00:06:32,490 --> 00:06:37,319
Such an approach will impact your performance
in a big way.

103
00:06:37,319 --> 00:06:38,319
6.

104
00:06:38,319 --> 00:06:40,300
Confirm divergence signals using volume

105
00:06:40,300 --> 00:06:46,320
Volume is one piece of information that is
often neglected by many market players, especially

106
00:06:46,320 --> 00:06:47,530
the beginners.

107
00:06:47,530 --> 00:06:52,770
However, learning to read volume brings many
advantages and could be of tremendous help

108
00:06:52,770 --> 00:06:55,270
when it comes to analyzing divergences.

109
00:06:55,270 --> 00:06:59,470
To correctly read the volume data, it must
be seen in the light of what the price is

110
00:06:59,470 --> 00:07:00,789
doing.

111
00:07:00,789 --> 00:07:05,379
So the implication of a trading volume depends
on the price movement.

112
00:07:05,379 --> 00:07:11,669
If the price is rising in an uptrend, a divergence
is visible, but the volume is reducing, it

113
00:07:11,669 --> 00:07:16,020
may show that there’s little interest in
the asset, and the price may reverse.

114
00:07:16,020 --> 00:07:21,900
Similarly, when the price is rapidly declining
and forms a divergence but the volume is low,

115
00:07:21,900 --> 00:07:25,919
it could mean that the institutional traders
are not interested in the price direction.

116
00:07:25,919 --> 00:07:28,990
So the price might soon reverse to the upside.

117
00:07:28,990 --> 00:07:34,530
A high volume after the divergence usually
indicates more interest in the asset and the

118
00:07:34,530 --> 00:07:36,740
presence of institutional traders.

119
00:07:36,740 --> 00:07:42,800
A divergence confirmed by a rising volume
represents one of the safest trades.

120
00:07:42,800 --> 00:07:44,669
7.

121
00:07:44,669 --> 00:07:48,210
Find confluence with common moving averages

122
00:07:48,210 --> 00:07:52,479
No matter how appealing a divergence signal
is, don’t take the trade without confirming

123
00:07:52,479 --> 00:07:55,150
the signal with some other type of analysis.

124
00:07:55,150 --> 00:07:57,680
You can do this by using confluence.

125
00:07:57,680 --> 00:08:01,830
Confluence forms in a spot where you have
more than one indication of where price will

126
00:08:01,830 --> 00:08:02,830
go.

127
00:08:02,830 --> 00:08:07,910
For example, confluence occurs where price
reaches a commonly used moving average.

128
00:08:07,910 --> 00:08:12,750
If in that point, you see a divergence forming,
you confirm your direction with the moving

129
00:08:12,750 --> 00:08:16,819
average, and you will have a stronger signal
and a higher probability of price going your

130
00:08:16,819 --> 00:08:18,749
way.

131
00:08:18,749 --> 00:08:22,729
Here is another example, when price touched
the simple moving average.

132
00:08:22,729 --> 00:08:28,749
We have a hidden bearish divergence on the
RSI and the RSI reached overbought area.

133
00:08:28,749 --> 00:08:30,499
8.

134
00:08:30,499 --> 00:08:34,350
Use higher time frames to trade divergences

135
00:08:34,350 --> 00:08:38,040
Divergence signals tend to be more accurate
on the longer time frames because you get

136
00:08:38,040 --> 00:08:39,830
less false signals.

137
00:08:39,830 --> 00:08:44,190
This means fewer trades but if you structure
your trade well, then your profit potential

138
00:08:44,190 --> 00:08:45,660
can be huge.

139
00:08:45,660 --> 00:08:50,270
Divergences on shorter time frames will occur
more frequently but are less reliable.

140
00:08:50,270 --> 00:08:55,020
That is why I advise you to look for divergences
on 1-hour charts or longer.

141
00:08:55,020 --> 00:08:58,340
Of course, there are many divergences on lower
time frames.

142
00:08:58,340 --> 00:09:03,480
But, on those time frames, there’s just
too much noise and the probability of a divergence

143
00:09:03,480 --> 00:09:06,040
to fail is higher.

144
00:09:06,040 --> 00:09:07,770
9.

145
00:09:07,770 --> 00:09:12,000
Use Ultimate Oscillator to trade multiple
timeframe divergences

146
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:16,910
The ultimate oscillator combines short-term,
intermediate-term, and long-term price action

147
00:09:16,910 --> 00:09:21,910
into one oscillator and offers divergence
signals that might warn of future price reversals.

148
00:09:21,910 --> 00:09:26,160
It basically measures momentum for three distinct
timeframes.

149
00:09:26,160 --> 00:09:30,650
The second timeframe is double compared to
the first, and the third timeframe is double

150
00:09:30,650 --> 00:09:32,280
compared to the second.

151
00:09:32,280 --> 00:09:36,290
Even though the shortest timeframe carries
the most weight, the longest timeframe is

152
00:09:36,290 --> 00:09:41,430
not ignored, which reduces the number of false
divergences.

153
00:09:41,430 --> 00:09:46,200
The ultimate oscillator generates fewer divergence
signals than the other oscillators due to

154
00:09:46,200 --> 00:09:50,910
its multi-timeframe construction, so the market
noise is greatly reduced.

155
00:09:50,910 --> 00:09:55,270
Of course, while the multiple timeframe trading
method for the indicator may help eliminate

156
00:09:55,270 --> 00:09:58,470
some poor trades, it also eliminates many
good ones.

157
00:09:58,470 --> 00:10:03,880
Therefore, it is sometimes necessary to change
its settings to reduce sensitivity and increase

158
00:10:03,880 --> 00:10:05,910
the number of signals.

159
00:10:05,910 --> 00:10:07,050
10.

160
00:10:07,050 --> 00:10:13,180
Don’t force divergence trades
When trading divergences, you must be careful

161
00:10:13,180 --> 00:10:15,650
and precise with your entry point.

162
00:10:15,650 --> 00:10:20,130
If you spot a divergence but the price has
already reversed and moved in one direction

163
00:10:20,130 --> 00:10:23,870
for some time, the divergence should be considered
played out.

164
00:10:23,870 --> 00:10:29,060
You missed the boat this time and it’s better
to stay aside and don’t force a late trade.

165
00:10:29,060 --> 00:10:34,260
All you can do now is wait for another swing
to form and start over your divergence search.

166
00:10:34,260 --> 00:10:35,260
Why?

167
00:10:35,260 --> 00:10:40,810
Because if you enter late, you alter your
risk:reward ratio for the trade.

168
00:10:40,810 --> 00:10:45,700
When trading divergences, the entry point
and risk/reward management are both important

169
00:10:45,700 --> 00:10:49,250
aspects that any trader should become familiar
with.

170
00:10:49,250 --> 00:10:54,040
If you miss a divergence entry, after the
price rejected a moving average for example,

171
00:10:54,040 --> 00:10:58,100
and you decide to enter after the price already
moved a lot, you will have to increase your

172
00:10:58,100 --> 00:11:02,900
stop loss, and if the trade doesn’t have
much profit potential, you will have a hard

173
00:11:02,900 --> 00:11:04,560
time managing your trade.

174
00:11:04,560 --> 00:11:08,810
Remember: there are always going to be other
divergence opportunities.

175
00:11:08,810 --> 00:11:11,160
The key is to be patient.

176
00:11:11,160 --> 00:11:15,971
If you found value and learned something new,
leave us a like to show your support, make

177
00:11:15,971 --> 00:11:20,190
sure you subscribe and click the bell icon
to stay notified when we release new videos.

178
00:11:20,190 --> 00:11:21,360
Until next time.

